{"key":"processedPost-16119407","value":{"id":16119407,"first":16117869,"last":16121727,"when":1335019736,"utime":"04/21/12 05:48 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>deucedbi9 said:</b><br /><br />I'd go with leave it alone.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />This is correct.<br /><br />The thing to remember is that mold spores have already landed on the surface of the substrate.&nbsp; If you stir this up, you put those mold spores under cover where they're protected and have a better chance of germinating.<br /><br />I use a 1:20 spawn to bulk ratio in my <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Mountain-Mushroom-Farm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">mushroom farm</a>.&nbsp; This results in an excellent yield, and as long as the texture and moisture content of the bulk substrate is right, it will colonize fast.&nbsp; Remember, once the mycelium starts growing, it picks up speed daily.&nbsp; It makes little difference in time to fully colonize using a 1:10 rate or a 1:20 rate.&nbsp; One can gain a few days earlier colonization by using a 1:2 or whatever, but as long as the substrate was properly sterilized or pasteurized, it's not necessary and a waste of spawn which would be better used to inoculate more bulk substrates instead of overloading just the one.<br />RR","title":"Re: Can you add more spawn after its started to colonize for 6 days?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}